1. tu: emphasizing the requests to his imaginary Leuconoe, whose name is chosen for its pleasing sound. By the collocation, quem mihi, quem tibi, Horace represents her as dear to him.—ne quaesi- eris: archaic and colloquial for the ordinary noli with the infini- five—scire nefas: parenthetical. Cf. Epod. 16, 14 nefas videre: and for the thought as well, Stat. T lzeb. 3, 562 quid crastina volveret aetas scire nefas homini.

2 f. nec: with temptaris, con- tinuing the prohibition, for the more common neve. — Babylonios

. numeros: tlte calculations of tlte, etc., employed in casting horoscopes.
